{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"3aee6b3b-e288-4535-a9ca-6f88bbac91d5","content":"On macOS, crash information is captured automatically by the system:\n\n**Crash Reports (always generated):**\n- `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` — user-level crashes\n- `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` — system-level crashes\n- Files are `.ips` (newer macOS) or `.crash` (older macOS), named after your process\n\nYou can also browse them in **Console.app** → Crash Reports.\n\n**Core Dumps (opt-in):**\n```bash\nulimit -c unlimited\n```\nThen re-run your app. Core files are written to `/cores/` (e.g., `/cores/core.<pid>`). You can analyze them with `lldb`:\n```bash\nlldb --core /cores/core.12345 ./MyApp\n```\n\n> **Tip:** On Apple Silicon, you may need to disable SIP or sign your binary with the `com.apple.security.get-task-allow` entitlement for core dumps to be generated.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"cd441aaf-5007-4071-a295-6aa592180e12","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about finding crash dumps/reports for a NativeAOT .NET application on macOS, without `createdump`. This is a general knowledge question — no tools needed.\n\nOn macOS, when an app crashes, the system automatically generates crash reports. Here's what I know:\n\n1. **macOS Crash Reports** are stored in `~/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for user-level crashes) or `/Library/Logs/DiagnosticReports/` (for system-level crashes).\n2. The files have extensions like `.crash` or `.ips` (newer macOS versions use `.ips`).\n\n\n3. I can browse these reports directly through Console.app, which provides a convenient interface for viewing them.\n4. For core dumps specifically, I can enable them with `ulimit -c unlimited`, and they'll be written to `/cores/`.","outputTokens":455,"requestId":"D81F:2657B6:5F3E7A5:6729261:69FBEFE3"},"id":"9ad045a0-1f61-43bf-959a-0dd469d6216d","timestamp":"2026-05-07T01:50:38.629Z","parentId":"0f3f9314-1ba8-4769-a28c-f722b845fbd6"}
